Publish incredibly high performance websites and applications right from GitHub. The Netlify platform connects your repositories to an all-in-one workflow for global CDN deployment, continuous integration, and automatic (and free) HTTPS. Each time you commit changes, Netlify builds your site, prerenders markup, and optimizes assets on dedicated build infrastructure. Easily create an entirely automated workflows for your web applications

## Features

### Push your site live, directly from GitHub
Deploy your site to an ultra-redundant global CDN thats purpose built for serving pages and assets quickly and consistently.

### Automate deployment
Netlifys built-in Continuous Deployment automatically runs your build commands and deploys the result whenever you push to your Git repository.

### Add a custom domain
Purchase domains and manage DNS zones and records right inside of Netlify.

### HTTPS is automatic
Your site will automatically be secured with a free TLS certificate from Lets Encrypt.

### Deploy Previews
Netlifys Deploy Previews streamlined your workflow by giving you a unique, permanent URL to check what your changes will be like in production whenever you submit a pull request.

### And a lot more!
Netlify includes solutions for forms, identity, and even custom functions powered by AWS Lambda. And all this functionality can be configured directly in your repo.

feat: add branches and checkout commands

Add a 'g' group for git commands to the application, within this
there are two new commands: branches, and co.

The branches command shows the branches available in the current
repository, and optionally searches them. The search is very basic
just checking for the search string within the branch name.

The co command uses the same logic as above, you can enter a branch
name that you'd like to checkout and it will search branches for a
match. If there is only one match, it will just check it out. If
there are multiple matches, then it will present an interactive
choice where you can use the TUI to select which branch you actually
want.

To implement the choices TUI, I used the bubbletea package. This
handles the interactivity for the app.

To implement the git commands, it is using the exec package, but i
introduced a service within the hostsys package to abstract this a
bit and avoid some duplication each time we need to call execute a
tool in the system.

While doing this I also introduced a logging package that we can use
to configure log levels throughout the app. As most of this is a
kind of TUI, the errors are presented anyway so the log level by
default is a custom "none" level that won't show anything. This log
level is a persistent flag that can be changed on each command and
will show more errors if needed for debugging.

pull_request.title: Fix ESLint React Hook dependency warnings in useEffect
pull_request.body:
Fixed ESLint React Hook dependency warnings that were causing CI failures on the copilot/fix-19 branch. The warnings were related to missing dependencies in `useEffect` hooks used for the rest timer functionality.

## Issues Fixed

**1. Missing dependencies in timer useEffect**
The timer effect was using `state.restTimer.startTime` and `state.restTimer.totalTime` inside the effect but not including them in the dependency array:

```javascript
useEffect(() => {
  // Uses startTime and totalTime but they weren't in dependencies
  const elapsedSeconds = Math.floor((now - state.restTimer.startTime) / 1000);
  const newTimeLeft = Math.max(0, state.restTimer.totalTime - elapsedSeconds);
}, [state.restTimer.isActive, state.restTimer.timeLeft]); // Missing startTime, totalTime
```

**2. Missing function dependency in notification useEffect**
The notification effect was calling `showRestCompleteNotification()` but not including it in the dependency array, which could lead to stale closures.

## Solution

- Added `useCallback` import from React
- Wrapped `showRestCompleteNotification` with `useCallback` to memoize the function and prevent unnecessary re-renders
- Added missing state dependencies to the timer useEffect dependency array
- Added the memoized function to the notification useEffect dependency array

The changes ensure proper React Hook dependency management while maintaining the exact same timer functionality. ESLint now passes without warnings, and the rest timer continues to work correctly for strength and hypertrophy workouts.

![Working app interface](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/0725796c-ad43-48c6-bf4d-d5bca6f46a1c)

Fixes #22.

issue.title: fix(utils): auto generated update method return

comment.body:
This change was introduced in https://github.com/medusajs/medusa/pull/12715. Judging from the description of that PR, it seems intentional, so there must be an misalignment/inconsistency somewhere that we need to update as well to prevent this from happening again.

Here's what I would expect in terms of behavior of the service methods:
```ts
createBrands({ name: "Hermes" }): Brand
createBrands([{ name: "Hermes" }]): Brand[]
createBrands([{ name: "Hermes" }, { name: "Rimowa" }]): Brand[]

updateBrands({ id: "br_1234", name: "Hermes" }): Brand
updateBrands([{ id: "br_1234", name: "Hermes" }]): Brand[]
updateBrands({ selector: { name: "Hermes" }, { coo: "France" }): Brand[] // Always returns an array, regardless of how many rows were updated
```

Could it be because our core services behave slightly differently in their method overrides? Maybe this has gotten us to mix this up. Wdyt?

cc @adrien2p

commits.message:
Enhance goals feature with comprehensive UI and functionality improvements

Major enhancements to workspace goals including entry linking, milestone management,
and improved user interface organization:

**Key Features:**
 Rename "RouterLink Entry" to "Linked Entries" across all components
 Add goal mapping in journal entry creation (step 4 of new-entry-modal)
 Support workspace/goal pre-selection when modal opened from specific contexts
 Reorganize goal actions into comprehensive three-dots Quick Actions menu
 Implement three-state milestone completion: incomplete  partial  completed
 Move category tags from bottom to top metadata row with other badges

**UI/UX Improvements:**
 Enhanced Quick Actions dropdown with milestone toggles, goal completion, and management
 Smart milestone progress calculation (partial = 0.5 weight)
 Visual milestone indicators:  (incomplete),  (partial),  (completed)
 Improved milestone counter display with partial completion indication
 Better tooltip information showing milestone status breakdown

**Technical Enhancements:**
 Update Milestone interface to support status field with backward compatibility
 Add linkedGoalId support in CreateJournalEntryRequest interface
 Implement useWorkspaceGoals integration in new entry modal
 Enhanced goal-journal entry linking with automatic workspace/goal pre-selection
 Comprehensive milestone state cycling with proper API integration

issue.body:
$2000 USD Bounty here!

If you can find a nice solution to our local dev experience, take home a $2000 USD bounty. We have a very strong feeling the culprit is the App Store. The problem is that refactoring it is a challenge since we have 100+ apps, there are tons of circular dependencies and our `main` branch is constantly merged to, making conflicts hard to work around.

Take these PRs as inspiration to ideally not load the entire App Store upon any given page load in our app. If you debug locally and watch what happens in the `.next/server/chunks` folder, you will see it's compiling a ton of code that's not needed.

These PRs have gotten close but refactoring the test suite to continue passing has been quite a blocker.

https://github.com/calcom/cal.com/pull/22450
https://github.com/calcom/cal.com/pull/19771

Current initial page load times per page even on a beast MacBook Pro can be upwards of 10-12s. **This needs to be cut by at least 80%.**

commits.message: Auto commit from Google Apps Script

shared-qmi: fix byteorder for supl server IP

It was noted, that when supl server is set using IP address. Modem
doesn't connect to the SUPL server anymore. When IP address is inverted,
then modem connects to SUPL server successfuly.

IP address is stored as uint32_t. According to Telit's documentation [1]
numeric values are encoded in little-endian format in QMI.

After converting IP address from string to binary using inet_pton
IP address is stored in network byte order (big-endian). Therefore it's
needed another convertion from big-endian to host endianness. Final
conversion from host endianness to endianness needed for QMI will be
done in generated
qmi_message_pds_set_agps_config_input_set_location_server_address.

Vendor's Android GNSS hal uses htonl() to convert from struct in_addr
(already in big-endian) before sending QMI request as well [2].

Tested on Quectel EG25-G and SDM845 (OnePlus 6T).

1. FN980 Family Telit Proprietary QMI Command Reference Guide. 4.1.3.1 Byte Ordering
2. https://github.com/ugly-kid-af/device_xiaomi_violet/blob/snow/gps/gnss/GnssAdapter.cpp#L1110

Signed-off-by: Andrey Skvortsov <andrej.skvortzov@gmail.com>

Merge request !1390 from 'fix/set-supl-server-ip'

shared-qmi: fix byteorder for supl server IP

https://gitlab.freedesktop.org/mobile-broadband/ModemManager/-/merge_requests/1390

modem-helpers: document mm_parse_supl_address()

More specifically, that the returned IP address is in network
byte order.

See https://gitlab.freedesktop.org/mobile-broadband/ModemManager/-/merge_requests/1390

Signed-off-by: Dan Williams <dan@ioncontrol.co>

Merge request !1393 from 'supl-ip-byte-order-doc'

modem-helpers: document mm_parse_supl_address()

https://gitlab.freedesktop.org/mobile-broadband/ModemManager/-/merge_requests/1393

shared-qmi: always set NMEA types

By default, the Pixel 3a only emits $PQXXX traces, even when all the
desired traces are reported as enabled. A request to set the NMEA types
must still be sent to enable the GGA/GSA/GSV traces. Remove the
optimization that prevents the request from happening automatically.

Signed-off-by: Richard Acayan <mailingradian@gmail.com>

shared-qmi: Lock and unlock GPS engine when starting and stopping

Newer modem firmware requires the use of the GPS engine lock, which
controls what the GPS engine can do. Set the GPS engine lock when
appropriate to handle this newer firmware.

Signed-off-by: Richard Acayan <mailingradian@gmail.com>

shared-qmi: Register NMEA types indication callbacks earlier

It might be too late to register the indication callbacks after the
response is received. Register the callbacks when the request is made so
an requested indication will always be handled.

Signed-off-by: Richard Acayan <mailingradian@gmail.com>

GNSS support for SDM670 devices

shared-qmi: fix setting URL to supl server

Function mm_parse_suple_address returns TRUE on valid input data
regardless of its type (URL or IP). As a result
qmi_message_loc_set_server_input_set_ipv4 was always called on valid
data. If URL was provided, then 0.0.0.0 ip address was sent to the
modem instead of provided URL.

Fixes: 6e84f3d4593 ("iface-modem-location: validate SUPL server address")

Signed-off-by: Andrey Skvortsov <andrej.skvortzov@gmail.com>
